Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgxcgNc1eNLRWR2oPd54AaABAg,,@kschneyer,"A lovely reaction! Thank you so much.

The great fiction writer Elizabeth Bear once told me that Rick is the classic example of a character in conflict with himself. Rick doesn’t understand what he wants. He begins the film believing that he wants to be left alone in his self-protective shell. Then he thinks he wants Ilsa. But at the end, he realizes he wants to be part of something bigger than himself. This was always true of Rick (think about his military and political past), but the pain of losing Ilsa makes him think he can only survive by caring about nothing. It is the return of Ilsa and the meeting of Victor that re-awakens in him who he really is.",2026-05-03T15:14:17Z,2026-05-03T15:14:17Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-11T02:01:32.469209
